<article>
    <h1>BIG PIC&#xAD;TURE Utah&#x2019;s salt lake shrink&#xAD;ing steadily</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201006/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-06"><time>2020-10-06</time></a>
        - <span>OPINION</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHOTO: EPA-EFE</span>
    </section>

    <p>A report last month said that the Great Salt Lake (above) in the United States is steadily shrink­ing ev­ery year.</p>
    <p>But the au­thor­i­ties in the state of Utah are im­ple­ment­ing mea­sures to slow the wa­ter loss and pre­serve the area, which plays sev­eral im­por­tant roles in the state.</p>
    <p>The lake is an im­por­tant re­source for Utah’s min­eral in­dus­try.</p>
    <p>It is also a pop­u­lar recre­ation spot and hosts sev­eral bird sanc­tu­ar­ies.</p>
    <p>Of­fi­cials warn that the shrink­ing wa­ter level could also cause in­creased air pol­lu­tion.</p>
    <p>The lake is the largest in­land body of salt wa­ter in the Western Hemi­sphere.</p>
    <p>It is also one of the most sa­line in­land bod­ies of wa­ter in the world.</p>


